ed Helplessness, Locus of Control and Attribution Theory -- tCHAPTER 35 The Social Child: Re-evaluating Piagetian Theory and the Socially Aware Child -- tCHAPTER 36 The Nature/Nurture Debate Continues: Types of Intelligence Testing and its Controversies -- tCHAPTER 37 From Helplessness to Optimism: Seligman and the Establishment of Positive Psychology -- tCHAPTER 38 Making Decisions: Everyday Judgements and the Use of Heuristics – Kahneman’s System 1 and System 2 Thinking -- tCHAPTER 39 Nodes, Networks and Neuroplasticity: The Classic Taxi Driver Study, Recovery from Stroke, Neural Networks and Social Emotions -- tCHAPTER 40 A Methodological Revolution: Deconstructionism and Decolonisation, Challenges to Orthodox Research Methodology and WEIRD Sampling -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA rich and engaging guide to psychology, the science devoted to understanding human nature What really drives our decisions? Where do language and memory come from? Why do our minds sometimes seem to work against us? Psychologists have long attempted to answer these questions, seeking to understand human behaviour, feelings, and thoughts. But how to explore something so elusive? In this fascinating history, leading expert Nicky Hayes tells the story of psychology across the centuries and around the world. Hayes introduces key thinkers, including Carl Jung, Anna Freud, Frantz Fanon, and Daniel Kahneman. We see how they tried to expand our understanding, from Pavlov and his dogs to Milgram and his famous electric shock experiments to the CIA’s secret mind-control projects. Hayes explores key concepts like child development, the inferiority complex, and PTSD and shows how psychological research has been used for both good and ill. This Little History shines a light on the ever-advancing study of psychology, how the field has evolved over time—and how much more we need to learn.  aMode of access: 